comments.message:
Depends, on the raspi it might be ppp0, but on mdm9xxx devices it's rmnet0.

I don't know if this runs in a sandboxed env, but you could eventually do something like:
 if [ -e "/sys/class/net/rmnet0" ]; then
   INT_NET="rmnet0"
 else
   INT_NET="ppp0"
 fi
Mix of tabs and spaces, should be spaces
Should we just remove this code?
Or something like "To trace command execution, uncomment the following line" ?
You can already include the -d flag for tracing commands, so it should be ok to remove.
Why channel 4? (Try to avoid magic numbers.)
That seems like a workaround for something, what is the issue behind this ?
It defaulted to channel 0 (which is invalid), but yeah this isn't the place for it.

The PiloT manual describes setting up an ECM interface, so that seems like the best one to use rather than serial.

Page 11: http://linkwave.co.uk/sites/default/files/PiloT%20USER%20MANUAL%20UM280716.pdf
aaahhh I'm too used to having the tab key generate spaces in sublime
Actually if you can make this file a README_raspi.md and use some markdown that might be better.
Actually maybe this should be in a doc, or in the demo folder, but not at the root.

Two spaces the end of a line creates a
in non-github markdowns, but actually yeah I'll change it to the code block way.

commits.commitMessage:
Correct errno check on strtol call

According to errno man page:
   errno
       The value in errno is significant only when the return value of
       the call indicated an error (i.e., -1 from most system calls; -1
       or NULL from most library functions); a function that succeeds is
       allowed to change errno.  The value of errno is never set to zero
       by any system call or library function.

Hence do not assume errno to be zero at the end of a successful system
call, unless errno is set explicitely to zero before invoking the system
call.

The strtol() function sets errno to ERANGE in case of an error. Set
errno to zero before calling strtol() and check against ERANGE on
return, to detect underflow or overflow errors due to bad arguments.

Resolves: LE-16338
Change-Id: Id35b8c2f46220ac4b6f3948ae95396b823271619
Signed-off-by: Anju Kunjumon <akunjumon@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: Correct errno check on strtol call

commits.commitMessage:
Resolve default legato system build error

The default legato system fails to build due to not being able to find the
wifiService app. This fix will adjust the include of wifi.sinc in
wifi.sdef as the default.sdef needs to include it when wifi is enabled.

Resolves: LE-15001
Change-Id: Ieccbaf021400c0e65c29004af2ebcce0a341a466
commits.subject: Resolve default legato system build error

comments.message: Could you please add a comment to clarify the use-case?

I can add a comment here. To my understanding, this use case is interesting as building wifi.sdef while LE_CONFIG_ENABLE_WIFI is not selected seems strange. It seems like it could be used for enabling the wifi apps while not using its interfaces for something like stand-alone wifi tests. Can anyone confirm this use case?

commits.commitMessage:
[Wifi] Implement new features for retrieve data

- Create three functions in le_wifiClient.c to get data from platform adaptor layer.
- Create new functions in pa_wifi_client.c to fetch data from iw command.
- Add new command in pa_wifi.sh to get data of access point.

Resolves: LE-12933
Change-Id: Idd1a57b310500e74408c87c6c260a999ffbb3c12
commits.subject: [Wifi] Implement new features for retrieve data

no hardcoded interface name, could be wlan1
this flag is not needed. This pa_wifiClient_AccessPoint_t is only used by WiFi
Do you need to goto cleanup?
It appears that this should be just a static function in this file; right?  If so, please remove the le_wifiClient prefix and name it as GetLinkResult().
Why pa_wifiClient_Link() and pa_wifiClient_GetLinkResult() can't be together as 1 pa_wifiClient function so that in pa_wifi_client.c you don't need IwLinkPipePtr as a static global variable?

pa_wifiClient_Link() and pa_wifiClient_GetLinkResult() can combine the same function, but I think because they perform two processes, Link and getResult (called after pa_wifiClient_Link() succeeded), we should split into two functions so that the code is clear and easy to maintain
If you insist on having 2 separate functions, pass IwLinkPipePtr than put it as a global static, as it is not used anywhere else.

Patch Set 1:

Hello all,

This is patching back the change-set of https://gerrit.legato/c/Legato/WiFi/+/52333. With the following changes:
 - Kconfig: New change. A new config option is added to include or exclude the wi-fi kernel modules in Legato build. The default is to exclude, except for wp77xx. The exception is because, wp77xx stable release already includes the good toolchain to support these modules.

 - wifi.sinc: The inclusion/exclusion of wi-fi kernel modules, now depends on the newly added config flag.

 - pa_wifi.sh: A new check is added at the start of execution of script. This checks for presence of kernel modules in /legato. If the modules are not found, then it knows that we are not ready for the legato way, and let /etc/init.d/tiwifi take care of starting and stopping TI WIFI. If the modules are found, script executes the same path as in https://gerrit.legato/c/Legato/WiFi/+/52333.

Could you please have a look?

commits.commitMessage:
[pa_wifi] Use TI driver kernel modules from Legato

Legato hosts the TI Wireless kernel modules to avoid crowding the
Rootfs in cases where WiFi extension card is not being used. This
patch is to enable the TI Wireless platform adaptor to use the
kernel modules hosted by legato.

- Configuration option is provided to choose to embed the TI Wi-Fi
  kernel modules in Legato
- tiwifi start and stop functionalities from
  /etc/init.d/tiwifi is brought in.
- TI Wi-Fi kernel modules are loaded the Legato way (using kmod)
  not Linux way (insmod) if the modules are found in Legato.
- GPIO access is made through sysfs, where supported.

Resolves: LE-14414
Change-Id: I2320017fb0c7d6d85cc13ebd950dd3800e7642a8
Signed-off-by: Anju Kunjumon <akunjumon@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: [pa_wifi] Use TI driver kernel modules from Legato

comments.message:

commits.commitMessage:
[pa_wifi] Use TI driver kernel modules from Legato

Legato hosts the TI Wireless kernel modules to avoid crowding the
Rootfs in cases where WiFi extension card is not being used. This
patch is to modify the TI Wireless platform adaptor to use the
kernel modules hosted by legato.

- tiwifi start and stop functionalities from
  /etc/init.d/tiwifi is brought in.
- TI Wi-Fi kernel modules are now loaded Legato way (using kmod)
  not Linux way (insmod) as the modules now reside in Legato.
- GPIO access is made through sysfs, where supported.

Resolves: LE-13652
Change-Id: I5cc56165f487c37e80aa84808ad7341d89c0ceb2
Signed-off-by: Anju Kunjumon <akunjumon@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: [pa_wifi] Use TI driver kernel modules from Legato

commits.commitMessage:
Replace sleep() with le_thread_Sleep()

Replaced sleep() calls with a new le_thread_Sleep() function that will use
nanosleep() instead of sleep() as sleep() is implemented with the SIGALRM signal
which may introduce some bugs.

Resolves: LE-8202
Change-Id: I071d89813c7b681f0d289429200e77d6a714da4d
commits.subject: Replace sleep() with le_thread_Sleep()

commits.commitMessage:
Do not call chmod on WiFi PA in pa_wifiAp_Init()

In c1c658b4bb535e31390b0a64de0866d6702ff574 code was added to
pa_wifiClient_Init to execute chmod on the WiFi PA script.  The code was
surrounded by a comment emphasized by formatting indicating "Temporary
fix", but it's not clear exactly what was being fixed.  Perhaps at that
time, Legato lacked the ability to add the executable permission in the
"bundles/file" section of the Component.cdef.  Later in
a9da26bd78e3784f7758b05cc4b68c95ba6ae2f6 the emphasis of the "Temporary
fix" comment was reduced.  Finally, in
b440d0f014a8037ca58da73841fb92ec8253103c the "Temporary fix" comment was
removed entirely (again without explanation).

In this commit, I remove the call to chmod entirely because the WiFi PA
script may be in a read only filesystem without any overlay and thus it
could fail.  If this happens, the WiFi service will be prevented from
starting.

If it is later discovered that there is in fact a reason why the
permissions of the WiFi PA must be modified at runtime, please use the
chmod C function (man 3 chmod) rather than calling system("chmod ...")
and provide a clear comment explaining why it's necessary.

Resolves: LE-13769
Change-Id: Ie4449d743a02e6fe7c829251ed60a4850a614776
commits.subject: Do not call chmod on WiFi PA in pa_wifiAp_Init()

commits.commitMessage:
[WiFi] Fix the Wifi AP mode with a workaround in dnsmasq

This is a temporary workaround. The current problem is that
WIFI AP is not able to redirect DNS query from the connected
device (cellphone) to the DNS server.

Workaround is give the connected device the true DNS server
address, instead of the WP device.

Resolves: LE-13807
Change-Id: Iee0930ae64510d6d6227e043ad740a0ca7d6e849
commits.subject: [WiFi] Fix the Wifi AP mode with a workaround in dnsmasq

comments.message: Better to say what contents this logic will pick up than what it assumes, i.e. "Retrieve IP addresses configured behind the nameserver keyword on all lines of RESOLV_CFG_FILE."

I think you only add a comma when dns isn't empty & you have new content to concat behind.
This present logic may end up with multiple comma back-to-back, or a comma at the end of the line.
good catch. will move this if clause into the below one.

If you strstr() for "nameserver " with a space at the end, you can save the strchr() below, as you can move your returned pointer strlen("nameserver ") characters down to get to the start of your IP addr. That's more efficient and can overcome a line starting with some spaces in front "nameserver".
Would this length be always correct? Would it assume the presence of \n, etc., that might not always hold?
Yes it will. In fact the "-1" is to accommodate the '\n' character.

Sorry for a late discovery/realization; concern: dns[] is overrun causing memory corruption. If by mistake or what, RESOLV_CFG_FILE has many more lines of nameserver configs than max 4.
Thus, it's better to check length before strncat() to make sure that the length of dns[] won't be exceeded.

commits.commitMessage:
Introduce wifi.sinc and wifi_samples.sinc

Introduce wifi.sinc as a building block for user SDEFs that require WiFi
functionality. This has the advantage of allowing the user to include
WiFi support into their own SDEF without forcing them to pull in all of
Legato's default.sdef the way the previous wifi.sdef did. Also introduce
wifi_samples.sinc which just includes the wifi sample apps. wifi.sdef
has been re-written in terms of these new .sinc files.

Resolves: LE-8695
Change-Id: I6a33ce4a718dc2a290ae8853434958a7e12399c2
commits.subject: Introduce wifi.sinc and wifi_samples.sinc

comments.message: Maybe make this a variable so that it can be selected at system build time without editing files?

I think the idea is that you can override LEGATO_WIFI_PA in your SDEF.  That's what we do for mangOH Yellow here: https://github.com/mangOH/mangOH/blob/7c0d09e628dc1a13268f0ee4d2fb12de811370fd/yellow.sdef#L14

At one time, LEGATO_WIFI_PA was a variable like "ti", but I didn't like that because it didn't allow the PA to exist outside of the Legato repository (e.g. mangOH repository).  That's how we arrived at the current behavior.

commits.commitMessage:
Add supporting QCA9377 WiFi chipset in Legato

Modifications:
    1: Add platform adapter code to support QCA9377 WiFi chipset
    2: Change channel data type to support larger channel number used in IEEE802.11a mode
    3: Reorder WiFi hardware start and event monitoring thread creation. QCA9377 WiFi
       driver needs the new order

Resolves: LE-12704

Change-Id: I95c7f05112ac730d889f5dc83e96ab3bc2d34f64
commits.subject: Add supporting QCA9377 WiFi chipset in Legato

comments.message: A LE_ERROR log wouldn't be better here ?
I have no problem with this change itself, but it has nothing to do with QCA9377 support. Maybe this should be in another commit.
The TI WiFi only supports 2.4GHz, so at that moment only init8_t is used. Now QCA9377 supports both 2.4GHz and 5GHz, so a larger channel number is needed.

I understand that the change to support more than 127 channels was necessary for 5GHz support.  

Your commit message currently has this:

> 1: Add platform adapter code to support QCA9377 WiFi chipset
> 2: Change channel data type to support larger channel number used in IEEE802.11a mode
> 3: Reorder WiFi hardware start and event monitoring thread creation. QCA9377 WiFi
>    driver needs the new order

When you find yourself writing lists of changes in a commit message, it's a sign that the commit should be split into multiple commits.  This makes it easier to revert, cherry pick and review.  Having said all that, there are many examples in the Legato git history of people grouping multiple independent changes into a single commit.  It's a bad practice and I think it should be discouraged, but it's not my job to be a gatekeeper for the Legato repository, so I'll +1 this.
I will keep it in mind. Thanks David.
It seems that these values should be in a public header file.  I know header files aren't usable from a bash script, but at least it would be more obvious than having to dig through the source code.
Moved them to pa_wifi.sh and pa_wifi_ap.h.
Please comment on why this is initialized to 7
Changed to 6 since in the 2.4 GHz band, 1, 6, and 11 are the only non-overlapping channels.
If 100 means "couldn't reset the wifi hardware", then why is the define PA_NOT_POSSIBLE instead of PA_RESET_FAILED?

There are some tiny difference between different drivers. For example:
1) TI wifi:
a) When TI wifi drivers are loaded successfully, if hardware is inserted, the WLAN interface exists by checking ifconfig -a
b) When bring up WLAN interface by issuing command ifconfig wlan0 up, sometimes it fails because firmware fails to boot. In this case, a reset can recover.

2) QCA wifi:
a) When QCA wifi drivers are loaded successfully, if hardware is inserted, the WLAN interface exists by checking ifconfig -a
b) When bring up WLAN interface by issuing command ifconfig wlan0 up, there is no special procedure to bring up the interface, the interface is always brought up smoothly. So no reset applies to this situation.

I will change the comments.
There's no need for explicit "exit ${SUCCESS}".  You can just let it complete the case and then exit naturally by reaching the end of the script.
It looks like some debug statements got committed
Uploaded patch set 2: Commit message was updated.

users to specify a full path to their own wifi PA implementation and
override ours.

comments.message: Please add inline comments to explain the possible return values of tiwifi and their meanings. Also seek to use defines than magic numbers in coding.

Does this cover the case with the Wifi card not inserted? I thought this is a case intended to be addressed here too. I just checked LXSWIREF-1355, which suggested 2 error codes: 50 (not-inserted) and 100 (failed-booting). 
Thus, what are the consensus and the resulting behavior for the former case?

If wifi card is not inserted, or some other reasons cause wifi card fail to start (not including firmware fails to boot), a wifi stop clean up is needed. So currently there is no difference to handle it. 

I will return the different reason code here so pa_wifiClient_Start (and le_wifiClient_Start) can get different fail reason. In the near future, the failure code can be used by upper applications calling these functions.

I would be inclined to simplify along these lines (note local variables as well):
CheckConnection()
{
    local retries=10
    local i=0
    local connected
    local ret=Success

    while [ $i -lt $retries ] ; do
        connected=$( /usr/sbin/iw $1 link | grep "Connected to" )
        if [ -n $connected ] ; then
            i=$retries
        else
            i=$(($i+1))
        fi
    done

    if [ -n $connected ] ; then
        ret=Success
    else
        ret=Error
    fi
}
This part works as expected. I just add indention here. Will not change it to avoid unexpected negative effect.
kill -9 will leave many things dangling. Do you really need to do it?
Test using kill ${pid}, does not work and cause process hang there

commits.commitMessage:
Add new wifi connection handler API to report more information

Issue Description
1: Ensure all device specific information is moved into platform adapter.
2: Pull out some common platform adapter codes into common folder

Modifications:
1: Remove all hard coded WLAN interface in Legato
2: Add WiFi connection event handler to report connection status,
WLAN interface name, BSSID of AP, and disconnect cause
3: Shared PA code is moved to common folder
4: Change the way to kill iw event thread
5: Remove the function to generatepsk to reduce overhead
6: Add more return status of pa_wifiClient_Connect
7: Refine WiFi connection commands
8: Add reset mechanism when wifi firmware boot fail
9: Add disconnect cause (enum type)

Resolves: LE-12118 LE-11677 LE-12487 LE-12255 LE-12525 LE-11776
Change-Id: Ibccc27d60e3f98059216a704918ad120afd46851
commits.subject: Add new wifi connection handler API to report more information

comments.message:
Klocwork [Critical NNTS.MUST #4463 @ wp76xx]

> Buffer overflow of 'tmpString' due to non null terminated string 'tmpString'

Sonar [MAJOR c:S1854]

> Remove this useless assignment to local variable "result".

Sonar [MAJOR c:S121]

> Add curly braces around the nested statement(s) in this "if" block.

Sonar [MAJOR c:S121]

> Add curly braces around the nested statement(s) in this "if" block.

Sonar [MAJOR c:S121]

> Add curly braces around the nested statement(s) in this "if" block.

Sonar [MAJOR c:S1854]

> Remove this useless assignment to local variable "ret".

Sonar [MAJOR c:S1862]

> This branch can not be reached because the condition duplicates a previous condition in the same sequence of "if/else if" statements

Sonar [MAJOR c:S1854]

> Remove this useless assignment to local variable "result".

Sonar [MAJOR c:NonReentrantFunction]

> Replace this call to the non reentrant function 'strtok' by a call to 'strtok_r'.

I seems that the platform apdatation is now entirely done in the pa_wifi.sh script. So I wonder if it makes sense to keep this code in pa_wifi_ap.c, perhaps it must be moved up into the le_ layer.
What do you think?

Hi Tristan:

I think so. I can do it if you, Anthony or Jon agree to move this part into le_wifiAp.c

I don't understand the purpose of moving this into the LE layer. Here, we call a platform specific interface (pa_wifi.sh script), these calls should be gather into a platform adaptor (it is the goal of a platform adaptor), exactly what is done here. So this file is fine to me.
OK, let's keep it like this

Klocwork [Critical UNINIT.STACK.ARRAY.MIGHT #4504 @ wp76xx]

> 'apBssid' array elements might be used uninitialized in this function.
Why is the interface name empty?  Isn't the interface name is applicable to scan results?

What is the purpose of the $LEGATO_WIFI_PA variable?  It seems like this would allow you to pick one WiFi implementation at build time.  It would be nicer if many WiFi implementations could be supported with a single build.
This variable is within Legato, so when build Legato, we can select which platform adapter to use. To support multiple WiFi cards working concurrently will be in the phase two as we discussed.

&wifiEventPtr->ifName[0] -> wifiEventPtr->ifName

Change this in all similar statements
The number of bytes used in tmpConfig is not being tracked.  This could lead to a buffer overflow.

Double the size from 512 to 1024 to reduce the risk. Add null terminator before pass the string to write function. Since the contents to be written into tmpConfig is controllable, the check for the total size in temConfig is skipped.
0x000F is a magic number.  What is significant about this group of bits in the bitmask?
It is a mask used to retrieve the hardware mode. It is replaced with a defined variable.

iptables commands are parameterized by the name of the interface, but otherwise they're generic for Linux.  The commands will be the same for TI, Qualcomm, Cypress and MTK wifi solutions.  For this reason, I think they could be taken out of the platform adapter.

The interface is platform dependent.
In addition, the size of this part is small, no hurt to put here.

I'm not sure that it makes sense to require the PA to exist in that specific location.  Wouldn't something like:

    [x] ${LEGATO_WIFI_PA_PATH}/pa_wifi.sh pa_wifi.sh

provide more flexibility?  This way a customer can provide their own PA without having to change the Legato source code directories.
It is platform adapter code. Users need to provide different adapter code based on different platform. It is up to users to select which file and which directory. Here it is a default sample.

I believe that scanIfName is only an [OUT] type parameter.  This function needs to take another parameter:

    size_t scanIfNameSize

which is used to tell the PA how much space they have to store the interface name.
Similar to accessPointPtr, scanIfName is both input and ouput. scanIfName is declared in le_wifiClient.c , the size is given there.
I assume this is sized such that all of the snprintf, strncpy and strncat calls below cannot cumulatively cause it to overflow?

It is the maximum size of the string passed to function WriteApCfgFile one time. To complete generating hostapd.conf, function WriteApCfgFile is called several times. It is easier for debug if something wrong.

Please don't change the equality test ordering.  Our coding standard doesn't explicitly state the ordering, and in general "Yoda syntax" makes it harder to read the code.  I won't give a -1 over it, though.

I change the order because Sonar Reports complaints the original order.
I will change it back to the original order.
Similar comment for these buffers.  Make sure that the various strncat calls, etc. can't exceed the buffer capacity.
This should be a defined constant.

commits.commitMessage:
Fix string handling warnings from GCC 8.2.

* apps/sample/wifiWebAp/wifiWebApComponent/wifiWebAp.c
(WifiEventHandler, StartWebServer): Here, the issue is that the buffer
used for formatting a time is of the same size (BUF_SIZE) as a buffer
which receives that time via a larger format string. GCC informs us that
we're trying to stick a string that might be to BUF_SIZE-1 characters
long into a formatted content that is itself confined to BUF_SIZE.
Since the time is nowhere near BUF_SIZE, the fix for this is to just use
a small buffer for the time string (that is HH:MM:SS).

* service/platformAdaptor/ti/pa_wifi_ap_ti.c (pa_wifiap_SetPassPhrase):
Replace strncpy and null termination steps with le_utf8_Copy based on
the destination buffer size.

Resolves: LE-12273
Change-Id: I616a43fb5654e1ab997999ea99c944e1fd8ecade
commits.subject: Fix string handling warnings from GCC 8.2.

commits.commitMessage:
Move Wifi security configs to secStore and complete support for all security protocols

This set of 2 code patches seeks to move Wifi security configurations from the config tree
to secStore to improve confidentiality. It thus also changes the recently added API
le_wifiClient_LoadSsid() to load security configs from the new secStore item locations.
Moreover, 4 new wifiClient APIs are implemented for configuring security protocols that
couldn't be configured before. With these, all the supported protocols including WEP, PSK,
EAP and open security become configurable and usable, and such feature gap is considered
sealed.

Resolves: LE-12257 LE-12242
Change-Id: Iddca11ee9e05f984dcc37ab05dd92723dc9ec9ce
commits.subject: Move Wifi security configs to secStore and complete support for all security protocols

comments.message: Belong to the old code. But I can take the chance to correct it, as far as it's minimal...
I just wonder what API or function to let users to set these passwords into secure storage before to read them.

As mentioned in the le_wifiClient.api documentation (start of the file), the corresponding le_wifiClient_ConfigurePsk, ConfigureWep, ConfigureEap APIs/functions are the one that has written/set such security configs in before they are read via this or similar functions. I can add a line to explain this further in this function's header comment to make it clearer.

It seems there are some restriction on psk or passphrase length. For psk, it has 64 hex digits. For passphrase, it contains 8~63 characters. Should we check these restriction here like

if (passPhrasePtrSize > LE_WIFIDEFS_MAX_PASSPHRASE_LENGTH || passPhrasePtrSize < LE_WIFIDEFS_MIN_PASSPHRASE_LENGTH) ? 

Here MIN_PASSPHRASE_LENGTH = 8.

For PSK, please see my reply below. For passphrase, I knew its min requirement at 8 but for backward compatibility reason didn't code up this enforcement here. You can see that dcsServer doesn't check it before passing it to le_wifiClient_SetPassphrase(). It lets le_wifiClient to do the work.
However, when you now bring this up, I re-think about it and agree that this is now code in le_wifiClient than dcsServer. Such error should be rejected as early as possible. Let me add it back. Though it might make some existing apps violating this requirement seeing this error in a different place earlier. But it should be a good thing, i.e. catching errors in config time than run time.

No, an app doesn't have to always provide an input buffer of the max length. E.g. if the app's provided PSK is "mySecret", it's completely fine to give that string and length 8 as inputs. Other Legato code behaves like this as well.

Sonar [MAJOR c:S1854]

> Remove this useless assignment to local variable "secProtocol".

commits.commitMessage:
Address issues uncovered by new GCC 8.3 warnings.

* apps/sample/wifiWebAp/wifiWebApComponent/wifiWebAp.c
(WifiEventHandler, StartWebServer): Here, the issue is that the buffer
used for formatting a time is of the same size (BUF_SIZE) as a buffer
which receives that time via a larger format string. GCC informs us that
we're trying to stick a string that might be to BUF_SIZE-1 characters
long into a formatted content that is itself confined to BUF_SIZE.
Since the time is nowhere near BUF_SIZE, the fix for this is to just use
a small buffer of 32 characters for the time string (that is HH:MM:SS).

* service/platformAdaptor/ti/pa_wifi_ap_ti.c (pa_wifiap_SetPassPhrase):
Here we have a strncpy whose limiting size is based on the source rather
than destination. The size is checked though, and so it is useless.
Since we checked the size we can just use strcpy.

Resolves: LE-12273
Change-Id: I5caee7ee56fcaf5233c5b7e58fcf01fbf6118bb4
commits.subject: Address issues uncovered by new GCC 8.3 warnings.

commits.commitMessage:
Reduce excessive Wifi logs and convert those ERR ones for legitimate failures to WARN

The wifiService has been generating lots of log messages and some are determined as errors
causing false alarms, although they are expected & legitimate for cases like where Wifi is
absent, Wifi can't start due to a wrong driver, etc. This code patch converts some INFO
logs into DEBUG logs and selective DEBUG logs into WARN ones.

Resolves: LE-12380
Change-Id: I2119a383b6aaae54aa7db21a687db43e29a7a466
commits.subject: Reduce excessive Wifi logs and convert those ERR ones for legitimate failures to WARN

comments.message: Personally prefer LE_ERROR here. There is Err in message.
No, Kevin. When Wifi is absent or the used driver unloadable, we don't want this printed as an error. A warning is more proper.

Nitpicking..
Should "Err:" (which implies error) be renamed to "return code" or something similar?
It is an error here right? Hardware is not stated, wifi can not work properly.

Same here, Kevin. When Wifi is absent or the used driver unloadable, we don't want this printed as an error. This is a wifiClient_Start(), which will be tried anyway unfortunately. A more sophisticated way is to have some way to check before blindly trying it.
Shristi, I'll update this log msg also.

Agreed that better way is to have some way to check beforehand.
Should "Failed" replaced to something that sounds like warning and not error?
Should this be an error or warning?
It's okay to be an error here, since if it has not been started, you won't be able to get it to try to stop it.
Not your change but there's a typo here. :)

Why 4?
Did you test this on WP76xx and WP85, running on both mangOH red and green ?

Patch Set 1:

As specified in the JIRA issue:
"In pa_wifi.sh, there are 25 retries to check the connection status of wifi. If the connection is established, the call can be returned immediately. If not, 25 seconds are occupied by this scripts."

If so, we must modify the loop to prevent to wait 25s. But, normally, it should exit when the wlan0 itf is available:
(/usr/sbin/iw $1 link | grep "Connected to") && break

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1
> 
> Why 4?
> Did you test this on WP76xx and WP85, running on both mangOH red and green ?
> Also, the 25 is a maximum value that. The loop exits when the ifconfig wlan0 is available. So it may be immediately, 1, 2, 10, 16,... up to 25, that in this last case, set the wifi failed.


Hi Christophe:

Actually I am thinking a question that do we really need to check the connection every time when we issue a wpa_supplicant connection request. Personally I think it may not be necessary. We issue a connection request command via system call, and currently we check the return status either 0 or other value. If return value is 0 (check connection return connected) then the return of system call is ok. If other value (either -1 or retries number). then the return of system call is failed. I suggest to not call check connection. The event handler will return the connection status. I issue the command, if the command is ok, then return 0 to system call, if system call is not executed normally, it will return -1. Connection can not be established (return the number of retries) can not be treated the system call failed. 

Currently the new DCS supports multiple sessions. If connection of one session can not be established, it takes 25 seconds, then let other connection to try.

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1:
> 
> > Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1
> > 
> > Why 4?
> > Did you test this on WP76xx and WP85, running on both mangOH red and green ?
> > Also, the 25 is a maximum value that. The loop exits when the ifconfig wlan0 is available. So it may be immediately, 1, 2, 10, 16,... up to 25, that in this last case, set the wifi failed.
> 
> 
> Hi Christophe:
> 

After wpa_supplicant is running, to establish a wifi connection, it will do authentication/association/(four-way handshake)/authorization. If signal strength is strong enough, the link can be established in a short time (a couple of seconds). If it takes a long time to try to get the link established, it means the signal strength is not good enough. Even if the linked is established at the marginal signal strength, the link will break frequently. Hence data still can not be transferred reliably. So in this case, it is not good to allocate a large number to retry. 

In addition, iw event will report the status of connection.

Patch Set 1:

The pa_wifi.sh script should report if the interface is correctly discovered. So, it has to wait the wlan0 interface becomes available to report its status. If the interface never came, that means the IoT board is not working. The modules are inserted, but they can failed to download the firmware or the initialize the board.
So, for me, we do not have to do something here.

Did you ask for an architect view (Anthony or Jon) ?

By the way, like the loop exits when the wlan0 becomes ready, I do not see any issue here.

Hi Christophe:

Thanks a lot for your quick reply and invite more reviewers. The interface (wlan0) is discovered in function ti_wifi_start() in /etc/init.d/tiwifi

--------------------------------
       [ -d /sys/class/gpio/gpio8 ] || echo 8 >/sys/class/gpio/export      
       echo out >/sys/class/gpio/gpio8/direction                           
       echo 1 >/sys/class/gpio/gpio8/value                       
                                                                           
       modprobe wlcore || exit 127                                         
       modprobe wlcore_sdio || exit 127                                  
       modprobe wl18xx || exit 127                                         
    fi                                                                     
    sleep 5                                                      
    ifconfig -a | grep wlan0 >/dev/null                                    
    if [ $? -ne 0 ] ; then                                                 
        echo "Failed to start TI wifi"; exit 127                         
    fi                                                                   
    ifconfig wlan0 up >/dev/null                                     
    if [ $? -ne 0 ] ; then                                       
        echo "Failed to start TI wifi"; exit 127                           
    fi 
------------------------------------------------
We need CheckConnection() in pa_wifi.sh, but the 25 seconds is too long. My suggestion is to reduce 25 to a smaller number.

comments.message: Is it possible to be connected to multiple AP simultaneously ? If yes, could we return a list of connected AP instead ?
It is impossible. Even when we support multiple Wifi services and drivers on the same device, the input AP or SSID reference would be unique and mapped to only one active Wifi connection.

Yes, you gave this same comment during the code review on dev-dcs. My response there was: 
"This code is now on par with what's in the old in le_data. If this code is to be improved, it needs be in both. Let's decide on it & do it separately. Please put your code improvement suggestion here into a new ticket."

But since code reviews really take such a long time to finish, let me do it in both le_data & le_dcs now, w/o using another ticket. After I re-submit the upcoming new code patches, please help to provide your CR+1 to both soon. Thanks.
This is real reason for my -1: these 2 tickets are checked-in !!

But this is a cherry-pick.  You mean that a ticket should only be moved to "checked-in" when no more cherry-pick merges under it are necessary?  Anyway, I've moved both the tickets back to "Start review".

Thanks. Tickets are moved to checked-in when all code is submitted on the main branch (I guess you are working on a development branch). Otherwise, the tickets may be considered as delivered into the next tag.

If you need to cherry-pick some patches from another "official" branch, you need a new ticket.

These kind of extra characters are boring for the review on Gerrit (if we have a lot, we will have a lot of red square on the screen everywhere). Could you please try to configure your editor to automatically delete them ? Thanks.
Yes, we'll not do those changes here, but in a separate patch under LE-12242. This code review has been going on too long which we need to wrap up & merge in 1st.

I think I provide enough information and code here. It can be merged in 19.02. Otherwise, the functionality is not complete.

But how to manage it is totally up to you.
Okay, but keep in mind that changing the config tree structure is an interface break, so it has to be done in the same release.

Sure. Currently, there is no breakage since there is no change for le_data while the config tree path used continues to be at dataConnectionService:/. What is added here is primarily used by le_dcs, which config tree path starts to be wifiService:/ instead of the former one. 
When the time comes to migrate le_data forward, we would remove the dataConnectionService:/ path. There a breakage would come.

commits.commitMessage:
Introduce KConfig for Legato build configuration

The KConfig settings subsume a number of disparate settings that were
previously controlled by various environment variables and preprocessor
defines.  The legacy environment variables are still used to populate
the initial values if no configuration is present, however the KConfig
output has become the single point of truth for these values going
forward.

The default behaviour of "make" and "make <target>" is preserved.  In
addition, "make menuconfig" and "make menuconfig_<target>" can be used
to explicitly change the configuration values.

The largest changes are the addition of the new KConfig files defining
the options, and extensive modifications to the Makefiles to generate
and use the configured values.  Most of the rest of the changes are
modifying preprocessor directives and values to use the new
configuration names.

Resolves: LE-10145 LE-10147
Change-Id: I24f0539b4e43df68340dfb184789a81a43871f1a
commits.subject: Introduce KConfig for Legato build configuration

Exit status WiFi scan not checked for errors

Updated the WiFi service to check the return code of excuting a WiFi scan and
returning the status to the client via an event.

Resolves: LE-9739
Change-Id: I6ad45f242a1c2173bedbf43576a09d1e922f0d5f
commits.subject: Exit status WiFi scan not checked for errors

comments.message: This looks like an accidental fall-through from the SCAN_DONE to SCAN_FAILED case.

The cast is unnecessary.  Can be changed to:

    le_result_t *scanResult = contextPtr;
If the xxxx_Scan() fails, we need to report it to scanResult here before return. Otherwise, we will get a scan done event from the destructor.

we can add something like: if (AddAccessPointToApRefMap() == NULL) { paResult = LE_FAULT; break}

This will cover the case where unable to add access point to the ref map.
Here too, need to report in scanResult, the returned value from ScanDone
I don't understand the purpose of this condition.
I'm not sure if we need to initialize this variable before starting a new scan.
Oussama not sure what you mean on this one as i am not initializing the ScanResult variable, what I am doing is passing the variable by reference so I can use it from within the thread.

ScanResult is a global. Suppose a scan failed. ScanResult will be LE_FAULT. Suppose we run the scan a second time, ScanResult that passed to the thread will be LE_FAULT.
However, since in the thread we doesn't care about ScanResult initial value. It's okay.

As discussed, if the script launched by popen hangs or doesn't end, we will stuck here.
I'll create a ticket for this issue and I'll attempt to treat it for all destructors.
Sounds good I will let you take that issue.
Declaration in pa_wifi.h should be updated as well.

commits.commitMessage:
Fix WiFi for secure networks

Currently the WiFi service is appending the networking info to a wpa_supplicant
file /etc/wpa_supplicant.conf which contains an existing network section for
unsecure networks. This is breaking connecting to a secure AP.

This was resolved by always re-creating the /tmp/wpa_supplicant file from
scratch and writing the unsecure network section from the PA adaptor code as
well.

Resolves: LE-9561
Change-Id: Ifc444c072d6105edccda53bc3e98c17000374329
commits.subject: Fix WiFi for secure networks

comments.message:
Do we need to make changes in WPA/WPA2 Enterprisse or not in order to get rid of the Open network ?
I'm not sure
Oossama not sure here have not tested wpa/wpa2 enterprise so assuming it is working

Oussama I had discussed a redesign with Jon Back that used a credentials object instead - this is on hold though for me as I only did a mangOH WiFi service implementation that supports multiple interfaces which the current version does not
There is no wpa_cli anymore, please update this comment

Yes they are used but in other use cases, not in this one. In COMMAND_WIFICLIENT_CONNECT_SECURITY_WPA_PSK_PERSONAL, we don't use WPA_CLI.

Check if `pgrep ... ` is not empty, else you will get error.
"pid=`pgref-f \""...\""`; [ -n \"$pid\" ] && kill -9 $pid"

Why return?
We could continue, here after and close the pipe else we will raise a lack of file descriptors.
In my view, I will first close the pipe (as it normally should kill the process attached by popen() and after, just in case, kill the process if it is still alive.

commits.commitMessage:
Prevent updating WIFI clients counter when start/stop APIs fail

A global counter in le_wifiClient keeps track of the number of clients 
currently using the service. The counter is updated when 
le_wifiClient_Start() and le_wifiClient_Stop() are called. 
This way, only the first start call starts the WiFi module and only
the last stop call shutsdown the WiFi module. 

This commit enhances the way the counter is incremented by preventing
any update if one of these APIs fail.

Resolves: LE-9174
Change-Id: I0042e8e31d3f3c3aac198ac3d0fedbacf14171a5
commits.subject: Prevent updating WIFI clients counter when start/stop APIs fail

commits.commitMessage:
Kill hostapd daemon when stopping WIFI AP

If hotapd daemon stays in background after stopping
AP then any attempt to relaunch the AP will result
in a failure. So, perform a hard kill terminate it
immediatly when stopping the AP.

My understanding (based on what dclark explained to me) is that the client will already register for connection status events so there is no point in blocking for an arbitrary amount of time to see if a connection is established.

Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

This changes the behavior of the API: currently, pa_wifiClient_Start() (and so le_wifiClient_Start() ) returns LE_FAULT is the connection failed (or can't connect). It will returns always LE_OK with this modification.
Are we sure that the connection/disconnection event handler is triggered if the start is failed (as there's no connection before, it is not a disconnection case) ?

Actually, this API is working like le_mdc_StartSession(), which is consistent to me.

And I've never heard a legato rule that "app should not block", many APIs are blocking. Watchdog timer has to be set accordingly.


It looks this patch was not pushed correctly as it has been submitted with https://gerrit-legato/#/c/23605/ , which is not correct (I think). Topic would be also set with the ticket number.

Patch Set 1:

> This changes the behavior of the API: currently, pa_wifiClient_Start()
 > (and so le_wifiClient_Start() ) returns LE_FAULT is the connection
 > failed (or can't connect). It will returns always LE_OK with this
 > modification.
 > Are we sure that the connection/disconnection event handler is
 > triggered if the start is failed (as there's no connection before,
 > it is not a disconnection case) ?
 > 
 > Actually, this API is working like le_mdc_StartSession(), which is
 > consistent to me.
 > 
 > And I've never heard a legato rule that "app should not block",
 > many APIs are blocking. Watchdog timer has to be set accordingly.
 > 
 > 
 > It looks this patch was not pushed correctly as it has been
 > submitted with https://gerrit-legato/#/c/23605/ , which is not
 > correct (I think). Topic would be also set with the ticket number.

Yes this would change the behavior - right now wpa_supplicant will try to connect forever so if the AP is down or the credentials are not right it will try connecting till its closed.  I double checked and there is no config option I could see to set a timeout.  There is no 'correct' watchdog timeout that can be set because of this.

It would be better to implement a timer in the WiFi Service for the connect timeout which could then notify the upper layers and disconnect.

As for blocking rule I have emailed Alex and Jen as I thought Alex told me this 2 years ago.

comments.message:
We are in multithreaded environment. localtime() is not thread-safe. Use localtime_r() instead.
See man 3 localtime
Why did this become a LE_FATAL? It was a LE_ERROR + return previously, which as fine, and now you changed it so it makes the application crash. I don't understand.
Seems like it should be just called once in the COMPONENT_INIT.

I was not aware that tzset needs to be called once.
There is another instance in legato code which is there wherein tzset is used in framework/c/src/clock.c - le_clk_ConvertToLocalTimeString

wherein there is a comment that tzset SHOULD be used before calling localtime_r

hence i have used it here as well.

If its mandatory to be called only once and only in COMPONENT_INIT. I will make the necessary changes.

Let me know.

As I understand, this function tzset() has to be called once.
And it is not mandatory to do it, because it is called by some time conversion functions: see https://www.gnu.org/software/libc/manual/html_node/Time-Zone-Functions.html

Moreover, I agree with the remark from Bertrand about doing this call once in the COMPONENT_INIT.

I disagree with the return... A file is opened in line 228; it must be closed, to avoid a leak of fd. In the same way, there are no report that the server is not started in that case. I am not sure that this should be an error raising a return. The call to strftime() should be prevent to be called and the function should continue ignoring the time.
Agreed, returning just for that is completely abusive.
if so, does it make sense to continue the function ? Or should we set a default value in tmp ?

Perhaps a memset(&tmp, 0, sizeof(tmp)); is required. In this case, the default time will be 01-01-1970 00:00 AM.
Else, we get the undefined values from the stack.

Undefined doesn't seem too good.
Can we at least have tmp = {0} to init the structure?

commits.subject: Check the value passed to the setmaxclients command

comments.message: you should follow the same prototype as the le_ function

The platform adapter is not supposed to be a simple copy/paste of the upper layer.
The upper calling function follows a certain "pattern" as it is supposed to eventually perform other additional tasks (calling several platform adapter functions for instance) while the platform adapter is supposed to do "one" thing.
Furthermore, the prototype used here, as a getter, induces systematically a returned value which is not conditioned to the validity of a parameter.

comments.message:
Why not using strlen(tmpString)? I think you missed the space in "(WIFI_SCRIPT_PATH COMMAND_WIFI_SET_EVENT)" with your computation.
Or you could use snprintf to build the tmpString.

strlen(tmpString) would rely on the fact that the string is terminated by a '\0', which is what we are trying to make sure of here.

I actually don't understand why we need that. Could you pinpoint which klocwork error you are trying to solve exactly? I can't find it.

The klocwork error is as below:

#1862: Buffer overflow of 'tmpString' due to non null terminated string 'tmpString'
/ws/work/legato/modules/WiFi/service/platformAdaptor/ti/pa_wifi_ap_ti.c:233 | WifiApPaThreadMain()
Code: NNTS.MUST | Severity: Critical(1) | State: Existing | Status: Analyze | Taxonomy: C and C++ | Reference: none | Owner: unowned
I will add this issue in klocwork false positive page.
How can you do a strlen on something that potentially doesn't have a null ending char?

tmpString contains this string: "/legato/systems/current/apps/wifiService/read-only/pa_wifi.sh wlan0 WIFI_SET_EVENT" with the help of combining WIFI_SCRIPT_PATH and COMMAND_WIFI_SET_EVENT macros.
So tmpstring contains NULL character.

Ideally, there should not be any requirements to set the NULL character tmpString.
But I am not understanding why klocwork gives error for tmpstring.

Should I have to record this error in the false positive page of klocwork ?

I have verified this logic with test code.

Ideally it is not required to add NULL for tmpstring.
I will add this issue in klocwork false positive page.

This change is necessary to support this use case:
$ export MANGOH_ROOT=/home/user/mangOH
$ export SDEF_TO_USE=$MANGOH_ROOT/mangOH_Red.sdef

$ export MANGOH_ROOT=/home/user/mangOH

commits.commitMessage:
No message returned when SSID is out of range

WiFi tool is now returning an error message.
The issue was due to a lack of control.
Besides a buffer overflow has been corrected.
Issue occured when the length of the SSID was precisely 32 bytes.
This has been log in LE-3507.

Resolves: LE-3500 LE-3507
Change-Id: I03e6d93559a4847b006331e1cdc588b74ce736cd
commits.subject: No message returned when SSID is out of range

comments.message: same remarks as for the other patch binds to this one.

Because SSID max length is limited to 32 bytes and LE_WIFIDEFS_MAX_SSID_BYTES is equal to 33.
Why 33? Because the SSID which should be exclusively managed as an array is sometimes managed as a string. So the 33th element is for the ending NULL character.
It was not the case previously and it led to a buffer overflow and/or an unknown SSID (see LE-3507).
coding rules, please use camelCase and Ptr suffix
The reference must not be exposed directly to the user here. It must remain hidden to him, I think a simple ID number is sufficient.

This is out of scope of the correction.
The comment is here as a reminder to know what is the argument and where to find it in the command line.
I think that your comment addresses LE-4311.
coding rules, must start with lower case letter
you should call LE_KILL_CLIENT instead of LE_ERROR
Why in this case not use printf() as done in the other file?

we don't log to standard output in our daemons.
Using print only makes sense in the case of binaries/apps launched by an operator
Why we can't delete an access point while a scan is running? I don't see any correlations.

Don't know as I didn't wrote the code.
But I guess it is done this way because it's easier and quicker than having to handle the release of resources (thread, variables, ...) or may be because the driver is in specific mode and it is wiser to wait. But it is just a guess as there is no documentation on how things work.
Missing description in doxy style for all varaiables and define

Totally agree.
Should eventually inform the original author and the reviewers about that and all the other things which are wrong in the code (not only this file).
This way, I wouldn't have to correct a reviewed and validated  code of at least 6 months old.
But the most annoying thing here is the way these variables are declared: globals. Perfect to generate unoptimized code (speed and size) and besides, it looks like afterthoughts.
if this code is only called by the daemon, you shouldn't log to the standard output

This is actually the purpose of the ticket.
To get an error message to the console when the user specify an invalid SSID. Otherwise, he will wrongly assume that everything is fine.

Something is strange here.
Why the -1 here?
SSID is not a null-terminated string.
SSID "12345678901234567890123456789012" will not work if I read this correctly.

Glad you catch the trick...
The problem is the SSID is sometimes handled as a string within the code.
I have to enlarge the size of +1 in order to host the NULL character, otherwise the SSID was truncated at 31 and then the SSID wasn't recognize (LE-3507) an it may eventually lead to a buffer overflow as the check of parameters are pretty light, which doesn't help with robustness... :)

You mean TOO long... :)
I would be happy if it was the only issue with the WiFi code...
